<subSubSection id="C3436526FFBEFF8429C9601AFEA9FE26" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE636ADFFBEFF8429C9601AFEA9FE26" blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis id="B92DEABFFFBEFF8429C9601AFEBDFEB3" bold="true" box="[199,321,260,285]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C594D2EFFBEFF842847601BFDD2FEB2" box="[329,558,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xenopygus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusus">
<emphasis id="B92DEABFFFBEFF842847601BFDD2FEB2" box="[329,558,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Xenopygus confusus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is easily distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D2EFFBEFF842A78601BFC27FEB2" box="[886,987,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Lesteva" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="analis">
<emphasis id="B92DEABFFFBEFF842A78601BFC27FEB2" box="[886,987,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">X. analis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C594D2EFFBEFF842D1A601BFB79FEB2" box="[1044,1157,260,284]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Xenopygus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bicolor">
<emphasis id="B92DEABFFFBEFF842D1A601BFB79FEB2" box="[1044,1157,260,284]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">X. bicolor</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the color of the head and pronotum, metallic blue to green, elytra yellow to dark brown, basal half of abdominal segment VII evidently darker than remainder of abdomen (
<figureCitation id="13622A28FFBEFF842B366052FD82FECA" box="[568,638,332,357]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 4" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1916,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,366,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,359,1894]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 4. Habitus. 2, Xenopyugs analis; 3, X. bicolor; 4, X. confusus. 5 – 7. Detail of head and pronotum. 5, X. analis; 6, X. bicolor; 7, X. confusus. Scale = 2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265268/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF842B616052FD82FECA" box="[623,638,332,356]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
) and sternite VIII of male with apical margin strongly emarginate at middle (Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF8428266071FEBBFE26" box="[296,327,367,392]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="35.0">35</number>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3436526FFBEFF8429C9608AFBE0FC0B" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BE636ADFFBEFF8429C9608AFC34FDB6" blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis id="B92DEABFFFBEFF8429C9608AFE88FE03" bold="true" box="[199,372,404,429]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">Redescription.</emphasis>
BL: 11.0–18.0 mm, BW: 
<quantity id="4CA19B48FFBEFF842B97608AFD0EFE02" box="[665,754,404,428]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="3.3" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" unit="mm" value="3.3">3.3 mm</quantity>
. Head and pronotum with metallic blue to green color, elytra and abdominal segments yellowish, basal half of abdominal segment VII evidently darker than remainder of abdomen (
<figureCitation id="13622A28FFBEFF84280060C2FEA8FE5A" box="[270,340,476,501]" captionStart="FIGURES 2 – 4" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1916,1938]" captionTargetBox="[151,1434,366,1894]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[151,1436,359,1894]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 2 – 4. Habitus. 2, Xenopyugs analis; 3, X. bicolor; 4, X. confusus. 5 – 7. Detail of head and pronotum. 5, X. analis; 6, X. bicolor; 7, X. confusus. Scale = 2 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265268/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF84284D60C2FEA8FE5A" box="[323,340,476,500]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="4.0">4</number>
</figureCitation>
). Pronotum with setal punctuations forming a pair of longitudinal lines in the median region and distributed in each lateral third, more evident in the anterior half (Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF842AA4631EFC46FDB6" box="[938,954,512,536]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="7.0">7</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE636ADFFBEFF8429C9633BFDB6FC96" blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
Eyes slightly longer than half of the head. Antennal scape slightly longer than antennomeres II and III combined; antennomere IV as long as wide; antennomeres V–XI with microsetae; antennomere XI apparently symmetric. Mesoventrite process with apex truncate and wide; and metatarsomeres II–IV slightly bilobate. Tergite III–V with arched carina; sternite VII of male with wide porous structure at middle (Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF842D8F638EFB5DFD06" box="[1153,1185,656,680]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="32.0">32</number>
); sternite VIII of male strongly medially emarginate (Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF842B3963AAFDABFD63" box="[567,599,692,717]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="35.0">35</number>
). Median lobe with bulbous base (
<figureCitation id="13622A28FFBEFF842AF963AAFBACFD62" box="[1015,1104,692,717]" captionStart="FIGURES 39 – 41" captionStartId="12.[151,264,1917,1939]" captionTargetBox="[200,1375,193,1872]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[200,1378,193,1876]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="FIGURES 39 – 41. Aedeagus, lateral view. 39, X. analis; 40, X. bicolor; 41, X. confusus. 42 – 44. Apex of median lobe, ventral view. 42, X. analis; 43, X. bicolor; 44, X. confusus. 45 – 47. Apex of paramere, dorsal view. 45, X. analis; 46, X. bicolor; 47, X. confusus. Scale = 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/265273/files/figure.png" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF842D3F63AAFBACFD62" box="[1073,1104,692,716]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="41.0">41</number>
</figureCitation>
); apex rounded and slightly truncate, subapically with tooth in hook shape in ventral surface (Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF842AB363C6FC21FD5E" box="[957,989,728,752]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="44.0">44</number>
); parameres fused in a single plate and almost reach the apex of median lobe, apex tightly truncate, apical two thirds with peg setae forming two irregular lines near the lateral margins (Fig. 
<number id="3D91248AFFBEFF842B10623EFDC2FC96" box="[542,574,800,824]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74" value="47.0">47</number>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BE636ADFFBEFF8429C9625AFF3FFC2E" blockId="15.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis id="B92DEABFFFBEFF8429C9625AFD22FCF3" bold="true" box="[199,734,836,861]" pageId="15" pageNumber="74">
